Are Natural Disasters an Indicator of Economic Crisis?¶

Introduction:¶

The world is undoubtedly getting warmer. According to a 2020 report by the World Meteorological Organization (WMO), the global mean surface temperature last year was approximately 1.2°C warmer than the pre-industrial baseline (1850-1900), and the most recent decade was the warmest on record. Throughout my project, I will be using the 'Climate Change: Earth Surface Temperature Data' to analyse and discover any drastic changes in regards to the increase in land or water temperature over time. I will use my findings and explore any natural disasters that have occured during those time periods. Overall, I am looking to find the time frame where we can see the highest increase in average land or sea temperature and figure out the reasons for these spikes in temperatures and their implications. Climate change can increase the risk of natural disasters in many ways, we know that it influences global temperature and precipitation patterns. This paper will specifically explore the direct relationship between natural disasters and global debt and argue that the rise in natural disasters due to climate change will result in higher global debt. With the steady rise in global surface temperatures, there will be a significant impact on the number, frequency, and duration of natural disasters, such as forest fires, hurricanes, heat waves, floods, droughts, and storms. For example, as more water vapour is evaporated into the atmosphere it becomes fuel for more powerful storms to develop. More heat in the atmosphere and warmer ocean surface temperatures can lead to increased wind speeds and tropical storms. Oxfam estimates the number of climate-related disasters has tripled in the last 30 years, and that more than 20 million people are being forced from their homes by climate change each year. This alarming number attests to the great impact global warming actually has on people's daily lives and is an issue that must be prioritised over the next couple of years.

Background:¶

Temperatures measured on land and at sea show that Earth's average surface temperature is rising. Land surface temperature is not the same as air temperature since the land surface heats and cools more quickly than air. Many physical properties have an impact on land surface temperature, such as: vegetation density, soil moisture and humidity, and snow cover or rainfall. Heat trapped by greenhouse gases stays near the land surface as well as being stored in the ocean. For this reason, the combination of land and ocean surface temperature data is a better indicator of global warming than air temperature. We might notice bigger changes in land temperature rather than water temperature due to water evaporation which occurs in liquid state. Oceans can cool themselves in a warming climate by evaporating water with only a small temperature increase, while on the other hand, land has a smaller heat capacity than water, which means it needs less heat to raise its temperature.

About the Dataset:¶

I am using dataset taken from kaggle.com compiled together by Berkley Earth. It combines 1.6 billion temperature reports from 16 pre-existing archives. There are 5 seperate datasets which include Global, Land and Ocean,and Land Temperatures which are sub-divided by: country, state, major city and city. This data set touches upon both land and ocean temperature data. However, it mainly focuses on land temperature as it is a more reliable measure and will experience more visible changes. However I will be adding additional datasets throughout the different stages of the projects.

Project 2¶

Since the beginning of the millennium, close to 1 billion people have been affected by natural disasters. To put this number into perspective, it is over 10% of the entire world population. Several of these disasters have injured people, some even fatally. Natural disasters kill, on average, 60000 people per year. However, this number highly varies from year to year, depending on unpredictable high-impact events. The damage and impact of natural disasters relies heavily on the intensity of the individual incident. Some catastrophic events, such as the 2010 earthquake in Haiti, represent a one-off incident that impacted around 3 million residents. The earthquake caused between 100,000 and 320,000 estimated deaths and widespread damage across Haiti. Such incidents are the reason why we cannot precisely estimate a trend by comparing two years with one another.

Flooding has been the most common natural disaster since the late 1900s. Over the last 30 years, around 10,000 natural disasters occurred globally, 42 percent being floods. Furthermore, storms, such as cyclones, hurricanes, and tornados, accounted for 30 percent of the total. Together, they cover nearly three-quarters of the disasters that have occurred since 1990. It is not a coincidence that global warming has the largest impacts on weather-related natural disasters such as storms and floods. Evidence suggests that climate change is to blame for the growing number of weather-related catastrophes such as droughts, hurricanes, and floods. With climate change creating more severe weather patterns, the risk to disaster-prone cities and regions continues to escalate. Many cities are geographically placed in risky areas. Near coasts, floodplains, and fault lines, making them vulnerable to floods, storms, earthquakes, and other natural hazards. This provides a fiscal strain on governments, due to the costly demands for relief and reconstruction increasing their budget deficits.

On the other side of the scale we have countries which barely had a temperature increase or didn't have one at all. The colder countries experience a larger change in temperatures, while the warmer ones not as much. According to the Norwegian Polar Institute the "Arctic is warming three times as fast and the global average. This is mainly because melting of snow and ice exposes a darker surface and increases the amount of solar energy absorbed in these areas" this is called the albedo effect. Colder countries are surrounded by more sea and land ice, differences in the amount of sea ice can disrupt normal ocean circulation, leading to changes in global climate. Significant increases in regional temperature can lead to continued loss of sea ice and therefore, greater warming over time, making the polar regions the most sensitive areas to climate change on Earth. My analysis supports this idea as we can clearly see from these two charts.

In 2018, the most recent datapoint, we see a peak of almost 5.2 metric tons per capita. This increase can be linked with our results in Figure 8. We noticed a high increase in the number of natural disasters in the recent 20 years. There is an association between the two, therefore, implying a causal relationship. This is further proof of natural disasters being affected by global warming and fossil fuel emission.

OLS Regressions - Finding the IV¶

One major issue that arises in an ordinary least square (OLS) regression is the correlation between the regressors and the error term, which is often called the problem of endogeneity. Due to endogeneity, the OLS estimates become inconsistent and therefore unreliable (Wooldridge, 2013). To fix this bias I used a 2SLS regression instead of OLS. The extent to which a natural disaster translates into global debt depends on many omitted factors which may differ from country to country, such as the post disaster management and institutional quality, among others. Therefore, it is useful to take endogeneity into account while using the natural disaster dataset to arrive at robust results. I started by finding a good Instrumental Variable (IV) for my independent variable, natural disasters. IV’s estimation is used when the model has endogenous x’s, i.e., if the covariance of the x variable and the error term isn’t zero. The IV addresses the problem of omitted variable bias. To choose the best IV I ran three OLS regressions against disasters, which were, greenhouse gas emissions, global land temperature, and land and ocean average temperature. The regressions are found below.

This plot is an OLS regression of natural disasters vs debt as a percentage of GDP. We notice a positive linear association between the two variables. As the number of disasters increases for the years 1966 - 2015 so does the debt as a percentage fo GDP. Furthermore, I will find the OLS summary to asses this relationship.

A regression model provides a function that describes the relationship between one or more independent variables and a response, dependent, or target variable

Given the plot, choosing a linear model to describe this relationship seems like a reasonable assumption.

We can write our model as

$$ {Debt}_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 {Disasters}_i + u_i $$

where:

  • $ \beta_0 $ is the intercept of the linear trend line on the y-axis
  • $ \beta_1 $ is the slope of the linear trend line, representing the marginal effect of disasters on the debt as a percentage of GDP
  • $ u_i $ is a random error term (deviations of observations from the linear trend due to factors not included in the model)

From the results, we see that

  • The intercept $ \hat{\beta}_0 = 24.93 $.
  • The slope $ \hat{\beta}_1 = 0.13 $.
  • The positive $ \hat{\beta}_1 $ parameter estimate implies that. institutional quality has a positive effect on economic outcomes, as we saw in the figure.
  • The p-value of 0.000 for $ \hat{\beta}_1 $ implies that the effect of institutions on GDP is statistically significant (using p < 0.05 as a rejection rule).
  • The R-squared value of 0.58 indicates that around 58% of variation in log GDP per capita is explained by protection against expropriation.

Using our parameter estimates, we can now write our estimated relationship as:

$$ \widehat{Debt}_i = 24.93 + 0.13 \ {Disasters}_i $$

This equation describes the line that best fits our data, as shown in the figure above.

Endogeneity - 2SLS¶

As we appear to have a valid instrument, we can use 2SLS regression to obtain consistent and unbiased parameter estimates.

First stage

The first stage involves regressing the endogenous variable ($ {Disasters}_i $) on the instrument.

The instrument is the set of all exogenous variables in our model (and not just the variable we have replaced).

Using model 1 as an example, our instrument is simply a constant and greenhouse gas emissions $ {Emission}_i $.

Therefore, we will estimate the first-stage regression as

$$ {Disasters}_i = \delta_0 + \delta_1 {Emission}_i + v_i $$

Second stage

Retrieved the predicted values of $ {Disasters}_i $ using the predict function

Then I replaced the endogenous variable $ {Disasters}_i $ with the predicted values $ \widehat{Disasters}_i $ in the original linear model.

Our second stage regression is thus

$$ {Debt}_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \widehat{Disasters}_i + u_i $$

As we can see when changing the x variable from disasters to predicted disasters the value for disasters changes from 0.13 to 0.17, meaning that we were overestimating the effect that an increase in disasters has on the public debt. We can now interpret the relationship of the model intuitively as, when the predicted disasters increase by one, the debt has an expected increase of 0.17 units. When looking at the value for R-squared, we see that 84.6% of the data fits the regression model. This value has increased from 58% which was the first OLS regression that was plotted for the variables. Additionally, we see the p value for the emission is still very small, below 0.000 therefore the results are still significant at the 0.01% level. The AIC and BIC are closely related and are indicators for the goodness of fit of a model. They have also decreased, which indicates a better fit model.

A one unit increase in natural disasters is related to a 0.1684% increase in the debt as percentage of GDP. The R-squared value suggests that 84.6% of the data fits the regression model.

An economic crisis can be defined as a situation in which a country’s economy deteriorates significantly. It is important that we make the distinction between the real and nominal terms. We call it a real economic crisis when it is adjusted for inflation with a fixed unit of currency. During the crisis, GDP is typically declining, liquidity dries up, and property and stock market prices plummet. It is an economic downturn that gets worse and worse.
In this study I have explored the effects of natural disasters on global and national debt using panel data from countries all around the world for the time periods of 1965 – 2015. When answering the question of “Are Natural Disasters an Indicator of Economic Crisis?” I would say yes and no. There is no definitive answer to this question, however, from the results of this project I have found an association between the occurrence of natural disasters and global debt.

In this project I have established the increases in global land temperature as well as, land and ocean temperatures over time. We can conclude the increases in global temperature are affected by pollution and greenhouse gas emissions. These two factors have the power to create numerous adverse effects both environmentally as well as economically. The main impact this creates is the occurrences of natural disasters. We can see that natural disasters may drive a world economy into a large amount of debt and devastations, similarly to the situation in Dominica in 2017. Global debt is an interesting concept which has been extremely prominent these past years. With the recent COVID-19 pandemic we observed the largest “one-year debt surge since World War II, with global debt rising to $226 trillion as the world was hit by a global health crisis and a deep recession” (Gaspar, et al., 2021). We cannot assume a strict relationship between natural disasters and public debt as there are countless confounding variables that impact debt. However, we may say that the rising of global temperatures and increasing emissions are indirectly affecting public debt through the increase in natural disasters.

In conclusion, the equation I found to represent the relationship between natural disasters and debt as a percentage of GDP is:

$$ {Debt}_i = 15.95 + 0.17 \widehat{Disasters}_i + u_i $$

Implying there is a positive linear association between the two variables, as the number of natural disasters increases so does the global public debt.

There are a number of future questions that should be investigated in this area of study. The rapidly evolving global climate is progressively getting worse and presenting as a critical cause for concern. According to Fankhauser (1995), health experts expect a rise in climate related diseases, such as heat strokes, and a spread of vector-borne diseases like malaria into so far unaffected areas. This is still very relevant today. We have seen spikes in heat related deaths, as well as famines due to crop and water shortages in the summers. Investigating the idea behind whether the death toll of natural disasters is actually decreasing despite the increases in occurrences could be a very interesting and important question to look into.
